The Kalends were on the first of each month: the Nones (ninth day before the Ides) on the fifth (except in March, July, October, and May, when they were on the seventh); and the Ides (root perhaps in ‘ di—vido‚' dividing the month‚) on the thirteenth, and in the four months enumerated on the fifteenth. In these months, up to the reform of the Calendar in B. c. 45, the number of days was 31, in the rest 29, except February, which was 28.
